      <hedline>
        <hl1>Trust in Government</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Roger Dobrick letter replies to Oct 5 letter deploring intrusion of government bureaucrats into people's lives, a theme of George W Bush's presidential campaign</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 5 letter posed a question -- ''are government bureaucrats more capable of running my life than I am?'' -- similar to what George W. Bush has asked in the debate and his stump speeches. To many of us, however, that is not the key question.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 5 letter posed a question -- ''are government bureaucrats more capable of running my life than I am?'' -- similar to what George W. Bush has asked in the debate and his stump speeches. To many of us, however, that is not the key question.</p>
        <p>Voters should be asking themselves if an increasingly unregulated and oligopolistic market economy should continue to prevent many Americans from access to basic  necessities, like affordable health care. I would also like to know why government is such an anathema to so many in a representative democracy.</p>
        <p>ROGER DOBRICK  Milwaukee, Oct. 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
